II. Emergent Physical Phenomena

This section outlines the primary behaviors reproduced by the Isostatic Metric Spacetime (IMS) framework. By modeling the vacuum as a rigid topological lattice, these phenomena emerge as structural consequences of the manifold.

Gravitation as Structural Tension: Within IMS, gravity is modeled as the emergent internal tension of an over-constrained network. Mass-energy localizations correspond to high-connectivity nodes, generating a redundant stress field that governs the attractive interaction between coordinates.

Derivation of the Inverse Square Law: The classic  decay of gravitational influence is recovered through the radial dissipation of topological stress in the three-dimensional rigid lattice.

Metric Recovery and Schwarzschild Geometry: Using shortest-path analysis (lattice geodesics), the IMS framework extracts the curvature component corresponding to the Schwarzschild metric. This establishes a correspondence between discrete lattice topology and continuous manifold geometry.

Topological Propagation: The constant  is interpreted as the maximum propagation rate of stress through the lattice. In this model, it arises as a mechanical property of the lattice’s rigidity rather than an externally imposed universal limit.

III. Theoretical Convergence

The IMS universe can be represented as a Rigidity Map. Gravitation is a structural consequence of network over-connectivity, and the 1.52 scaling exponent functions as a fundamental parameter controlling lattice growth and long-term stability.
